strong.span: Ready to Work addresses essential skills that our employers tell us is a critical part of being successful in the workplace environment. Many of our seniors are at home right now and this is a great time to get ready for college and/or the workforce.

strong.span: Upon completion the students will earn two industry-recognized credentials, as well as a free 3 or 4 hour course at Snead. The first class begins April 27th, and employers are waiting to interview students upon completion. A typical face-to-face RTW class will last 6 weeks. This virtual option may take much less time.

p.span:
MONDAY, MARCH 16, 2020
For parents and guardians of students who attend Marshall County Schools, milk, fruit, vegetables, tea, juice, and yogurt will be available on a first-come-first-serve basis today, March 16, 2020 from 1:30 - 3:30 at each lunchroom. We ask that families bring their own grocery bags to be filled. A drive through system will be utilized. Look for guidance as you enter the campus. Claysville parents may pick up at the DAR campus.

p.style: color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; min-height: 30.8px;
color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal;
p.span: Additionally, some Alabama internet providers are providing free internet services during this time to student homes. Other internet options are available on our website at www.marshallk12.org.

p.style: color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; min-height: 30.8px;
color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal;
p.span: For clarification, packets are for practice and are not a requirement. They are available in front of each school. Students who have devices and internet access will have practice opportunities online. Links are posted on our webpage.

p.style: color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; min-height: 30.8px;
color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; margin: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal;
p.span: We appreciate efforts and support from everyone to keep our students, staff, and communities safe. Our thoughts and prayers are with you and your family during this time.

div.span: On the evening of March 13, 2020, Governor Kay Ivey declared a State of Emergency for the State of Alabama. Although the press release stated dates of school closure, a local decision has been made to modify dates. Marshall County Schools and all school facilities will be closed beginning Monday, March 16. Current plans are to reopen Monday, April 6. All school-related activities are canceled beginning Monday, March 16, including athletics, athletic practice, prom, and all other extracurricular activities. We know how important these activities are to our students and will make every effort to reschedule at a later date.

Resources and links for students to use for practicing reading, math, and other academic skills can be accessed by visiting www.marshallk12.org. Printed skills practice packets will be placed in a sealed container in the front of all schools for parents to pick up if they choose to.

Contact information and other resources such as a listing of local food banks will be located on our website. We have received several calls from individuals and churches from our incredible communities asking how they can help. We encourage all who would like to give to the cause to donate to our local food banks.

Thanks for all you do. We will get through this.
Dr. Cindy Wigley
